<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Reed lifts profits by 4% to Pounds 232m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REED International, the publishing and information group, warned yesterday
it expected the pace of recovery from recession in its most important
markets to be slower than in previous cyclical upturns.
The warning came from Mr Peter Davis, the Reed chairman, as he announced a 4
per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds 232m for the year to the end
of March. The half-year to September had seen a 22 per cent fall in pre-tax
profits to Pounds 85.3m.
The Reed chairman confessed that a note of optimism expressed with the
interim results had turned out to be premature, though there were now some
signs 'which could turn out to be positive'.
Reed's operating profit rose 9 per cent to Pounds 271m, earnings per share
were 4 per cent higher at 29.3p, and operating cash-flow was up 32 per cent
at Pounds 293m - 108 per cent of operating profit.
Reed said its dividend for the year would increase by 7 per cent to 16p.
Reed's share price rose 6p to 580p on the London Stock Exchange in response
to the news.
Mr Davis said the results achieved during the recession were 'further
evidence of the benefits of the strategy to concentrate on publishing and
information businesses'. In spite of advertising-based businesses being
severely hit, the profit margin on sales was 16.6 per cent.
Five years ago Reed took a strategic decision to get out of manufacturing
businesses such as paint, pulp and packaging and concentrate on publishing.
The results of that decision are being assessed as part of a review of
strategy.
Further consolidation is likely, although acquisitions will probably
outweigh disposals. One acquisition, if it became available and if the
financial terms were right, might be the Official Airline Guides, bought by
the late Mr Robert Maxwell.
Among the main Reed businesses, consumer publishing suffered a 22.9 per cent
drop in operating profit to Pounds 52.4m, business-to-business publishing
saw a modest improvement of 9.6 per cent to Pounds 36.4m, exhibitions rose
26 per cent to Pounds 30.5m, and reference publishing soared 64 per cent to
Pounds 31.8m.
Lex, Page 26
