FT  04 JUN 92 / Observer: Painful
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A black day it was for Lloyd's of London chairman David Coleridge, and not
simply because of new forecasts putting the insurance market's losses for
1989 at Pounds 2bn, a fifth higher than previous estimates. He's also
chairman of Sturge Holdings, Lloyd's biggest agency.
The news from Sturge was that it expected to cut its annual dividend by
half, so trimming Coleridge's income from his 6.8m share stake by Pounds
559,324. But that's not all. Following a savage reaction from the market,
which pegged the shares down 59p to 111p, the value of Coleridge's stake has
plunged from Pounds 11.56m to Pounds 7.55m.
