<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Commons to hold debate on Maxwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR will next week use its first opportunity of this parliament to choose
the subject for debate to call a full-scale Commons debate on the plight of
the Maxwell pensioners.
The move came as the all-party group of MPs campaigning on behalf of the
pensioners yesterday wrote to to Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the governor of
the Bank of England, requesting him to explain why he had refused to
intervene.
The group will also be writing to the main banks in support of appeals from
the Maxwell pensioners themselves.
Mr Frank Field and Mr Richard Page, the group's co-chairmen, said that the
real focus of the discussion was the urgency of the pensioners' plight.
Mr Michael Meacher, shadow social security secretary, will open the debate
on Tuesday, which is expected to concentrate on the need for compensation
for the pensioners. Depending on how the motion is drafted, even Tory MPs
campaigning on behalf of the pensioners might find it difficult to vote
against it.
Last night's meeting of the Maxwell group of MPs agreed to appeal to its
100-plus members to press ministers at Commons questions today about when
the government expects to publish the report by the Securities and
Investments Board into the oversight by the Investment Managers' Regulatory
Organisation (Imro) of Bishopsgate Investment Management, the fund
management company owned by Robert Maxwell which managed the assets of his
company pension funds.
The SIB is said to be concerned that parts of the report may be deemed
libellous and is said to have been told by its solicitors that it may not be
exempt from libel actions.
MPs agreed that to try to avoid this problem, they would press the
government to publish the report as a House of Commons paper, so that the
specific approval of the Commons would then be needed before it could be
used in any legal action.
The House of Lords is to debate the position of the Maxwell pensioners
today, but the junior minister replying is unlikely to be able to pre-empt
the announcement from Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, about
a review of pension law and regulation.
</TEXT>
