FT  04 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Shares call to NatWest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES of the Mirror Group Newspapers pension scheme have called on
National Westminster Bank to stop delaying and return Pounds 31m in shares
which had been passed to the bank as collateral for a loan to Robert
Maxwell, Norma Cohen writes.
Mr Colin Cornwall, independent chairman of the trustees, said that
pensioners face the immediate loss of their pensions because the schemes are
running out of funds to pay them. 'A large part of the funds missing from
the Maxwell pension schemes went to various banks, including NatWest,' he
said. 'NatWest have been thinking about this for six months now and it is
time they made a decision.'
NatWest has said it will take its civic responsibilities into consideration
when deciding whether to return the shares. It has said it believed the
security to be sound, to have been properly taken and its rightful property
in lieu of loans not repaid by Mr Maxwell.
The bank, however, has declined to return the shares, saying the matter is
still under investigation.
