<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / House prices 'are still weak'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES remain weak and are showing little sign of recovery apart from
the small pick-up which usually occurs at this time of year, according to
Halifax, Britain's biggest building society.
The society, which yesterday published its latest monthly house-price index,
said prices last month rose 0.4 per cent. After taking into account seasonal
fluctuations, prices actually fell 0.5 per cent, it said.
It was the seventh successive month that seasonally adjusted prices had
fallen. On this basis prices had risen only once during the past 12 months,
in October, said the society.
Since April last year the average UK house price of Pounds 62,709 had fallen
6.2 per cent. Prices of new houses had fallen 6 per cent over the same
period to an average price of Pounds 73,629.
Halifax said there had been an improvement in demand since the general
election, but it was no more than it expected at this time of year. The
society added that it expected a further improvement in confidence. As a
result, it forecast that prices would stabilise in the second half of the
year before starting to rise next year.
Nationwide, the UK's second largest building society, has also reported a
small rise in house prices in April. Earlier this week it said prices had
risen 0.6 per cent in April.
Mr John Hutchinson, a Nationwide director, said: 'It is too early to
speculate that this is a sign of a general sustainable improvement.
'People may be less cautious now about making the long-term commitment to
house-buying than they were a few months ago, but there will be need to be a
demonstrable improvement in the economy and in peoples' job security and
confidence before the housing market gets going again.'
</TEXT>
