FT  04 JUN 92 / Wren Group compulsorily wound up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, LAW COURTS CORRESPONDENT, and RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WREN GROUP, of Sutton, Surrey, was compulsorily wound up in the High Court
yesterday on a petition by the provisional liquidators of Payroll Services,
a group subsidiary that is under investigation by the Serious Fraud Office.
The unopposed petition was based on an inter-company loan of Pounds 20m
between Payroll Services and Wren Group and was supported by the Inland
Revenue, which is a creditor for Pounds 710,000.
The SFO is investigating how Payroll Services, which serves more than 500
banks and financial institutions around London, allegedly diverted more than
Pounds 24m PAYE and National Insurance payments from the Inland Revenue.
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm acting as provisional liquidator to
Payroll Services, says the SFO is also investigating the Wren Group and the
directors of the companies.
The Inland Revenue has extended an informal moratorium on the payment of the
missing taxes.
However, it has told clients of Payroll Services that they will have to make
a second payment if the missing funds are not recovered.
