FT  04 JUN 92 / GE wins Dollars 150m contract to equip Medway power plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Electric of the US has won a contract worth more than Dollars 150m
(Pounds 82m) to equip the new Medway electricity generating power plant at
the Isle of Grain in Kent with gas and steam turbines.
The company will supply two gas and one steam turbine generator for the
660MW plant owned by Medway Power, a joint venture between Seeboard and
Southern Electricity - two of the regional electricity companies - and AES
Corporation of the US. The plant is due to start operation in 1995.
GE said yesterday that the Medway contract was its first independent power
plant project in Europe. It was also its first direct European sale of its
9F model, the world's most powerful gas turbine. Previous European orders
have been through GE's network of business associates.
GE and its partners claim to be world leaders in the gas-turbine generation
business. But Westinghouse of the US teamed up this week with Rolls-Royce,
UK aero-engine and industrial power group, to challenge GE's leadership.
Rolls-Royce yesterday announced its first order for an environmentally
friendly combustion system for the industrial derivative of its RB211 jet
engine. Pacific Gas, the US pipeline operator, has ordered three of the
systems for engines being installed in Idaho and Washington for service in
1994.
The new Rolls-Royce process, using a system to reduce oxides of nitrogen and
carbon monoxide emissions, is designed to meet environmental legislation
expected to be introduced soon in many of the company's power markets.
