<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Clean-up warning to building groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION companies should reduce noise, wasteful consumption of
materials and energy and clean up building sites and improve their
environmental record, according to a report published by the industry
yesterday.
The report by the Construction Industry Employers Council, which represents
the industry's biggest trade associations, warns that companies face big
fines and directors and employees face imprisonment if they fail to comply
with environmental legislation.
The report, produced by a task force led by Mr Peter Costain, chief
executive of Costain, one of the country's biggest contractors, says the
industry should seek to reduce waste on building sites by 50 per cent by the
year 2000.
It should also cut energy consumption, establish clear standards for
reducing noise and encourage better design, landscaping and land use.
'If we don't, others will and the industry will find itself increasingly
sidelined by ever-increasing amounts of legislation and competition from
abroad,' says Mr Costain.
The report also says all companies should establish an environmental policy
with well-defined objectives.
Marley, the UK building materials group, yesterday launched a scheme to
recycle waste plastics from building sites, in collaboration with Second
Life Plastics, British Polythene's recycling division. Marley said many
building materials were supplied shrink-wrapped in polythene.
A similar scheme launched by Second Life and the farmers' union had resulted
in 4,000 tonnes of polythene film being recycled last year. The Prince of
Wales yesterday renewed his attack on modern urban development and said that
it was partly to blame for the 'horrendous' social problems of inner cities.
Speaking at the launch of a report from the Urban Villages Group, he called
on architects, planners and developers to create living conditions which
enhanced human values.
He commended the report, which covers issues such as location, design and
planning, management, finance and community involvement. It advocates the
creation of 'mixed-use urban developments on a sustainable scale', creating
communities 'where people actually want to live'.
The group was established by Business in the Community in 1989 to
investigate how cities could be made better places to live and work.
Construction and Environment. BEC Publications, Federation House, 2309-11
Coventry Road, Sheldon, Birmingham. Pounds 15 members, Pounds 25
non-members.
Plastics Recycling scheme. Telephone 0800-833749.
Urban Villages. Urban Villages Group, 5 Cleveland Place, London SW1Y 6JJ.
Pounds 22.45.
</TEXT>
