<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Dollars 19.7m: and that includes the disco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS built as a favourite toy for a brother of arms dealer Adnan
Khashoggi. Then Robert Maxwell bought it and it became his favourite toy
until his death in November.
Now a glossy 12-page brochure for the yacht the Lady Ghislaine is being
distributed by international shipbrokers Camper Nicholsons in an attempt to
whet the appetite of as yet unenthusiastic buyers.
Although ship brokers originally mooted a price of Dollars 24m for the 180ft
yacht, Camper Nicholsons, with the agreement of Maxwell administrators
Arthur Andersen, has settled for the 'negotiable' price of Dollars 19.7m
(Pounds 10.8m).
The cost of the brochure is being kept secret, in apparent deference to
pensioners who lost money through Maxwell pension funds. 'Marketing expenses
are a complicated arrangement between broker and seller. In this case us and
the administrators,' said Mr Nicholas Baker, Camper Nicholsons' chief London
representative, yesterday.
In its introductory promotion blurb, the brochure tells us that the yacht,
built by the Dutch Amels shipyard, 'has it all'. It is in fact the largest
private yacht in the UK after the Royal yacht Britannia and Gerald Ronson's
My Gail III.
There is no mention in the brochure of Robert Maxwell. However, Mr Baker
conceded yesterday that the boat's association with the one-time media
magnate had 'helped' fuel market interest.
The Lady Ghislaine's special characteristics include a glass-bottomed
whirlpool bath, a sumptuous owner's bedroom and 'staterooms', and a main
saloon with a discotheque area including state-of-the art hi-fi equipment,
strobe lights and an octagonal mahogany dance floor.
We have been asked to point out by Oxford United Football Club that Mr Kevin
Maxwell resigned from the board on May 14, 1992.
Parliament, Page 14
</TEXT>
