<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Swift action to block cartels urged by Borrie
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should press ahead quickly with legislation to prevent
cartels emerging in industry, Sir Gordon Borrie, the director-general of
fair trading, said yesterday.
Sir Gordon, who retires this month after 16 years in the job, said that in
his final meeting with Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
he had urged him to introduce legislation as soon as possible.
He warned banks in particular that the OFT was watching them to see if they
were operating cartels. He said: 'Small businesses do not have a lot of
choice when it comes to banking services.'
He added that although there was no direct evidence of a cartel, there was a
great deal of concern over the introduction by several banks of charges for
setting up overdrafts.
He also referred to the OFT's fears that the Lloyds bid for Midland might
reduce competition in high street banking. He said: 'When one of the majors
(banks) decides to try and take over another of the majors, one can only
wonder whether this might not make the problem worse.'
The OFT feels that although it has been effective in tackling cartels in
some industries - such as construction materials manufacturing - its present
powers are too limited for it to be sure whether cartels exist in some
industries.
Total complaints to the OFT were 750,000, 8 per cent up on 1990. There was a
particularly steep increase in the numbers of complaints about financial
services, especially about banks and estate agents.
More than 4,000 complaints were received about banks, 63 per cent up on last
year. There were 2,477 complaints about estate agents, 58 per cent up on
1990.
Financial services were well below many other industries for the number of
complaints. The largest category was about house building, fittings and
appliances. There were nearly 237,000 complaints in this category but the
total was slightly down on 1990.
</TEXT>
