<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Pay falls for staff posted to Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COMPANIES are significantly cutting pay packages for staff
transferred to continental Europe, according to the Confederation of British
Industry, Michael Smith writes.
Most will be offered transfers abroad on terms matching those for locally
recruited staff, possibly with temporary allowances for housing costs and
children's education.
The research, by the CBI and Mercer Fraser, the consultancy, is based on a
survey of nearly 200 companies. Half employed more than 2,000 people
worldwide.
Companies cited competition, containing costs and the need for equity in the
workplace as the main reasons for reconsidering the remuneration of
expatriates in Europe.
Most organisations provided some sort of assistance with housing but many
were considering ending this system.
</TEXT>
