<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / US calls meeting of Latin American finance ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Latin America Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Treasury has called a surprise meeting of finance ministers from
Latin America to discuss trade, debt and investment developments in the
region.
The meeting, expected on June 24-25, will be chaired by Mr Nicholas Brady,
US treasury secretary, and is aimed at furthering the Enterprise for
Americas Initiative announced by President George Bush two years ago.
Mr David Mulford, under secretary for international affairs at the US
treasury, said yesterday he did not expect the meeting to yield any new
initiatives. But it would provide a useful forum to discuss the global
economy ahead of the summit of the Group of Seven industrialised nations in
Munich early next month.
Finance ministers have been invited to Washington from 11 governments which
have reached a Brady debt reduction accord with creditors or benefited from
the Enterprise for Americas Initiative. They include Brazil, Argentina,
Mexico and Venezuela but also smaller economies such as Jamaica, Costa Rica
and El Salvador.
Mr Mulford said that since the Enterprise for Americas Initiative was
announced there had been important progress in resolving debt problems and
stimulating capital flows in Latin America.
Good progress was being made in trade talks with Mexico and Canada on a
North American Free Trade agreement and once an agreement had been reached
the US would start negotiations on a similar accord with Chile.
The Enterprise for Americas Initiative was dealt a setback in April by the
failure of Congress to vote relevant authorisations and appropriations for
debt reduction and the US contribution to a proposed Dollars 1.5bn
multilateral investment fund.
Mr Mulford said the administration would continue to press this issue in the
current year.
</TEXT>
