<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Berlin to keep disputed properties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE COLITT and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BERLIN'S city government said yesterday it would take over more than DM10bn
(Pounds 3.4bn) worth of properties in east Berlin, instead of allowing their
former owners to claim them.
Mr Steffen Kammradt, spokesman of the Berlin Finance Office, said the
decision, taken on Tuesday night, would end the deadlock in rebuilding east
Berlin, caused by rival property claims. The ruling is expected to be
legally challenged by former owners.
The decision runs counter to a previous recommendation by the German
government that the properties, which were confiscated by occupying Soviet
forces shortly after East Germany was established in October 1949, should be
returned to their previous owners.
Mr Kammradt estimated that 'considerably more' than DM10bn worth of property
would be affected.
Among the most valuable real estate to revert to the city is a sprawling
site on Leipziger Platz, which had belonged to the Jewish-owned Wertheim
department store chain, now part of the Hertie group.
Prime sites owned by the Hohenzollern family, descendants of the former
emperor of Germany, were also affected by the decision.
A total of 589 companies and 951 property sites, mainly in the inner-city
Mitte district, is being claimed by the city, although it represents only a
small proportion of all buildings that might be subject to claims by former
owners.
Mr Kammradt said city-owned property could now be developed by investors who
might include some of the former owners.
It was up to the Bonn government to decide whether restitution would be paid
to former Jewish owners, their heirs or the Jewish Claims Commission, he
said.
Under the German unification treaty, three categories were excluded from
claims made by former owners: property confiscated from former Nazi
activists, from war criminals and from buyers of property owned by Jews
forced to sell in the 1930s.
Berlin's government said it had approved the merger of three state-owned
banks, creating one of Germany's top 10 financial institutions, Reuter
reports from Berlin.
The Berlin state government said the city's coalition of Christian Democrats
and the Social Democrats had approved the merger of Berliner Bank,
Landesbank Berlin and Pfandbrief-Kreditanstalt.
The new company will be called the Berliner Banken Holding AG and will start
operations in 1994. Approval clears the way for the city to draft a law to
put the three institutions under one roof.
'It will now be possible to finance large projects in Berlin,' said Mayor
Eberhard Diepgen.
</TEXT>
