FT  04 JUN 92 / Ukraine to end credit guarantees from July
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Ukrainian National Bank plans from July 1 to end government guarantees
on enterprises' payments from creditors, in a major step forward in
piecemeal efforts at market reform.
The move, which is scheduled to coincide with Ukraine's new law on
bankruptcy, is backed by parliament.
It comes as part of an effort being made by Mr Vadim Hetman, the tough new
head of the Ukrainian National Bank, to end a practice which has allowed
Ukrainian enterprises to rack up a Rouble546bn internal debt.
Under the current system, when purchasers do not pay, sellers are
compensated with credit issued by the National Bank.
Moreover, according to Mr Hetman, Russian enterprises have amassed a one
trillion-rouble debt to Ukrainian enterprises, although other government
officials concede that the size of the debt between Ukraine and Russia
depends on whether it is calculated in 1991 or 1992 prices.
At the most recent meeting of the leaders of the members of the Commonwealth
of Independent States, Ukraine pressed for an assessment and settlement of
inter-republican enterprise debt, but the proposal was rebuffed by Russia.
Mr Hetman said that debts between Ukrainian enterprises and debts between
Ukraine and all CIS republics, with the exception of Russia, will be
calculated at a meeting on June 11 and 12.
