<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Money Markets: Sharp futures drop
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING futures contracts traded at considerably lower levels yesterday as
uncertainty swept the money markets about the future of European Monetary
Union.
The decision of the Danish people not to participate in EMU caused
uncertainty in all sterling futures trading, as dealers questioned the
principle of monetary convergence in the long term and the strength of
sterling in the immediate future. Fears that EMU is in danger encouraged
foreign exchange traders to invest heavily in the D-Mark, and pushed
sterling briefly below DM2.92 in the afternoon. Believing that a weaker
pound may hinder the possibility of a base rate cut in the Autumn, futures
traders pushed contracts down.
Trading in an 11-tick range, the September contract closed at 90.25, having
closed at 90.35 the previous night. Yesterday's closing price suggests that
the market believes that the 3-month interbank rate in September will be at
9.75 per cent.
The December contract was even more heavily affected. Trading in a 12-tick
range, it ended the day at 90.48 from a previous close of 90.60. That
suggests that the market believes that 3-month Libor at the end of the year
will be at 9.52 per cent.
Rates in the cash markets were less heavily affected, because the Bank of
England forecast a small shortage of Pounds 100m. The Bank did not operate
at all during the day.
As a result, money remained cheap, with most players able to square their
books at an overnight rate of 8 per cent. That cheap rate fed through to the
short periods. 1-month money ended the day at 9 15/16 per cent,  1/16 per
cent softer than the previous night's close. However, 3-month money, a key
indicator of the way the markets think rates are moving, ended at 10 1/16
per cent, up  1/16 on the previous close.
The cash market in Danish krone was strongly affected by the referendum
decision. Denmark raised the 14-day Certificate of Deposit rate from 9.85
per cent to 10.5 per cent.
In Germany, call money eased slightly after the Bundesbank made a generous
allocation of funds in this week's tender for repurchase funds. A net
DM8.3bn flowed into the market, and call money eased to 9.65 per cent from
9.70.
</TEXT>
