<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / International Company News: Mercedes-Benz cuts 10,000 jobs
in wake of pay deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STUTTGART
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MERCEDES-BENZ, the automotive subsidiary of Daimler-Benz, the German
engineering group, is responding to the recent 5.8 per cent wage award to
engineering workers by cutting up to 10,000 jobs this year.
According to Mr Werner Niefer, group president, the pay deal will increase
costs this year by DM600m (Dollars 373m). If the company tried to pass this
on by increasing prices, customers would simply buy other makes, he told a
press conference.
Despite a 14 per cent increase in car and commercial vehicle sales during
the first four months of this year - already slackening after the 17 per
cent surge recorded in the first three months - Mr Niefer warned that 'a
fundamental recovery in our most important foreign markets is not yet
discernible'.
The post-unification boom in the German market was also tailing off. Even
so, the company, mainstay of the Daimler-Benz engineering, aerospace and
electronics group, planned to sell 560,000 cars, the same as last year.
The group turnover target was DM70bn, compared with DM67bn in 1991. Profits,
which resisted the general economic downturn last year and matched the
previous year's DM1.5bn result, would again be 'good', according to Mr
Helmut Werner, deputy president.
According to Mr Niefer, the international car market will at best stagnate
in the current year. 'The German market shifted back into normal gear during
the first four months,' he added. As a result, he expected total domestic
registrations to fall by 9 per cent. They were already down 6 per cent at
the end of April.
Indications of a 'hesitant upswing' in other west European countries would
compensate in part for the trend in Germany. The US was more encouraging, Mr
Niefer said. Mercedes sales there, led by the costly S-series and mid-range
cars, rose 18 per cent in the first four months while the overall market
increased only 2 per cent.
The early increase in world sales of commercial vehicles, up 7 per cent in
the first four months to DM102m, is expected to fade later in the year.
Again, falling demand at home is expected to be covered by rises elsewhere.
In the US truck and bus market, which grew 12 per cent in the first four
months, Mercedes increased its sales of heavy-duty lorries by 9 per cent.
Confirming plans to reduce the group's workforce by 20,000 'in the coming
years', Mr Niefer said most would go in Germany, where 183,000 of the total
235,000 workforce is employed.
News of the the loss of between 8,000 and 10,000 his year, following
Tuesday's announcement of a further 850 job cuts at Porsche, and plans for
massive cuts elsewhere in the German automotive industry, indicates
widespread concern at the loss of international competitiveness.
 ----------------------------------------------------
                   MERCEDES-BENZ
          First quarter group sales (DMbn)
 ----------------------------------------------------
                                    1991     1992
Western Europe                     14.15    15.78
Germany                             9.36    10.60
Western Europe (excl Germany)       4.79     5.18
US                                  2.43     2.65
Other markets                       3.59     4.61
 ----------------------------------------------------
Total                              20.16    23.04
 ----------------------------------------------------
