<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / People: Prentice to bond boutique
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sheldon Prentice, one of a diminishing group of bankers to have stayed the
course in the Eurobond market since its early days, has been appointed
non-executive chairman of Luthy Baillie Dowsett Pethick &amp; Co, a London-based
firm which specialises in trading illiquid Eurobonds. The firm was set up
two years ago by four other old hands of the Euromarket, Peter Luthy, Iain
Baillie, John Dowsett and Jan Pethick.
Prentice left Salomon Brothers last December after a career spanning nearly
20 years. He joined the firm in New York in 1973, then moved to London in
1977, where he ran the new issues business of Salomon Brothers International
for close to 15 years, latterly as a managing director of the company.
He was also on the board of the International Primary Markets Association, a
trade association for banks and securities firms active as arrangers of
Eurobond issues.
He succeeds Andrew Large who resigned to take up the chairmanship of the
Securities and Investments Board.
</TEXT>
