FT  04 JUN 92 / Newcastle's monument to shopping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GEORDIE shopping phenomenon entered a new phase yesterday with the
opening of a 50-unit retail mall in the centre of Newcastle upon Tyne.
The Monument Mall, adjoining Eldon Square - which claims to be Europe's
largest city-centre shopping complex - will strengthen Newcastle's hand in
competing against the MetroCentre, Europe's largest out-of-town shopping and
leisure centre, just across the River Tyne in Gateshead.
The Monument Mall is the only retail scheme to be opened in Britain this
year by St Martins Property Corporation, which has reined back development
because of the recession. Construction of Monument Mall cost Pounds 23m; the
scheme's total value including its site and shop outfitting will be about
Pounds 70m.
Although only part of the second floor was ready to start trading for
yesterday's low-key opening, 15,500 shoppers visited the mall in the first
four hours.
Quite why Tyneside, the centre of an area with Britain's highest regional
unemployment rate, should be such a mecca for shopping is constantly
debated. One big factor is relatively low mortgages compared with the
south-east giving good levels of disposable income for those in work.
