<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Call for 'green' facts in company reports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES SHOULD provide information on the environmental impact and risks
they face in their annual reports, the 100 Group of leading finance
directors recommended yesterday.
The group's environmental working party concluded that companies should
normally devote at least one page in the narrative section of their report
to the issues.
It did not specify in detail the information that should be provided, but
the group's statement of good practice says companies should invest time in
identifying environmental priorities and reporting on them accordingly.
They should report on responsibilities, monitoring procedures and
achievement of targets and start to develop verifiable information which can
be independently audited. The chief executive's report should reflect
commitment to the issues, it added.
Mr Bob Carlton-Porter, working party chairman, said: 'There are good reasons
for companies to disclose environmental information voluntarily.'
The paper cites Imperial Chemical Industries and British Steel as two
examples of current best practice.
Environmental reporting in annual reports. 100 Group, c/o SKB House, Great
West Road, Brentford, TW8 9BD. Free.
