<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Pay packages fall for staff transferred to Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COMPANIES are significantly cutting the pay packages they offer to
staff transferred to jobs in continental Europe, according to a survey by
the Confederation of British Industry.
This means that expatriates will no longer be able to bank all or most of
their salaries while living on generous allowances or incentive payments.
Most will be offered transfers abroad on terms matching those for locally
recruited staff, possibly with temporary allowances to cover local housing
costs and children's education.
The research, by the CBI and Mercer Fraser, the consultancy, is based on a
survey of nearly 200 companies. Half had a turnover of Pounds 200m or more,
and half employed more than 2,000 people worldwide.
Foreign-service premiums, included in the traditional packages as an
incentive for working abroad, were considered no longer applicable to the
Continent.
Most organisations provided some sort of assistance with the housing needs
of people transferred abroad, but many were considering ending this system
because of its cost and to bring the housing more into line with that of
locals.
Companies, however, regarded assistance for the education of employees'
children as sacrosanct.
Miss Sue Shortland, head of the CBI's relocation group, said: 'A common
salary structure will make transfers easier. However, there are serious
barriers in the way - like tax, pension and social security systems.'
</TEXT>
