<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Berlin to take contested properties: City acts to end
deadlock over more than DM10bn in rival claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE COLITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BERLIN'S city government, in a landmark decision, has ruled that more than
DM10bn (Pounds 3.4bn) in east Berlin properties claimed by companies and
private individuals will instead be taken over by the city.
Mr Steffen Kammradt, spokesman of the Berlin Finance Office, said the
ruling, expected to be legally challenged by former owners, allowed the city
to end the deadlock in rebuilding east Berlin caused by rival property
claims.
He estimated that 'considerably more' than DM10bn in property was affected.
Among the most valuable real estate to revert to the city is a sprawling
site on Leipziger Platz, near the former Berlin Wall, which previously
belonged to the Jewish-owned Wertheim department store chain, now part of
the Hertie group.
Prime sites owned by the Hohenzollern family, descendants of the former
German Kaiser, were also affected by the decision.
A total of 589 companies and 951 property sites, mainly in the inner-city
Mitte district, are being claimed by the city.
The decision runs counter to a previous 'recommendation' by the German
government that the properties, which were confiscated shortly after East
Germany was established in October 1949, should be returned to the previous
owners.
Only properties previously confiscated by the Soviet occupation
administration (SMAD) from former Nazi activists, war criminals and persons
who 'aryanised' Jewish property in the 1930s were not to be given back. This
was acknowledged by the Germans in their unification treaty of 1990.
The Berlin Justice Office, however, issued a legal opinion this week that
East Germany's confiscation of the east Berlin properties was merely an
administrative act carrying out a sovereign decision in 1946 by the SMAD.
Mr Kammradt said the way was now clear for the city-owned properties to be
developed by investors who could well include some of the former owners.
It was up to the Bonn government to decide whether restitution would be paid
to former Jewish owners, their heirs, or the Jewish Claims Commission, he
said.
</TEXT>
