<TEXT>
INVESTIGATIONS into Milan's multi-billion lire corruption scandal have taken
a decisive turn with the arrival in Rome of legal papers calling for
parliamentary immunity for five politicians implicated in the inquiry to be
lifted.
The list includes two prominent Socialists, Mr Carlo Tognoli, the outgoing
minister of sport, and Mr Paolo Pillitteri, elected to parliament in April.
Both are former mayors of Milan, and Mr Pillitteri is the brother-in-law of
Mr Bettino Craxi, the Socialist party leader.
Separately in Milan, the role of big industrial companies has come further
into the spotlight with the decision by Mr Ivo Braglia, the head of the
transport division of the Italian subsidiary of the multinational Asea Brown
Boveri (ABB) engineering group, to testify voluntarily before investigating
magistrates.
ABB is one of a number of big engineering companies which supplied equipment
for the city's third underground railway line, which has been one of most
important infrastructure projects being investigated by magistrates.
Until now, inquiries had focused on Fiat's Cogefar-Impresit construction and
civil engineering subsidiary. Its managing director, Mr Enzo Papi, has been
in prison for the past month as a result of his refusal to co-operate with
magistrates.
