<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 92 / Italians pick former communist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A BROAD cross-party coalition yesterday elected Mr Giorgio Napolitano, a
veteran former communist and member of the Party of the Democratic Left
(PDS), as Speaker of Italy's chamber of deputies.
Mr Napolitano, 66, was proposed by the PDS and backed by the Christian
Democrats, Socialists, Republicans and Social Democrats. The same alliance -
without the Republicans - led to the election on May 25 of Mr Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro, the then-Speaker, as Italy's ninth president.
Despite misgivings and internal divisions, Mr Achille Occhetto, the PDS
leader, has thus twice in recent days led his party into alliances with his
former opponents, the Christian Democrats, or rivals, the Socialists. He has
said this does not commit the PDS, the second largest party in parliament,
with 16 per cent of the vote, to form part of the next government; but it
has set a precedent.
Another sign of change in the political scene has been a statement by
President Scalfaro that he would like the next prime minister to form a
cabinet of his own choosing and not depend upon the traditional dictates of
the party bosses. With a new Speaker, the formal process of consultations to
form a new government can now begin.
The election of a PDS Speaker was seen, in part, as a trade-off for
supporting Mr Scalfaro's election to the presidency. Mr Napolitano had been
proposed two months ago for the job, when parliament first convened after
the April 5 general elections; but the Christian Democrats pressed for one
of their own in the form of Mr Scalfaro.
Neither the Christian Democrats nor the Socialists backed the PDS's first
candidate, Prof Stefano Rodota, the party's president and former visiting
law fellow at All Souls, Oxford. The Socialists, in particular, view him too
much of an internal PDS choice. Prof Rodota was forced to withdraw after
four rounds of abortive voting, and yesterday resigned as party president.
The party's decision to drop his candidature has provoked criticism of Mr
Occhetto's leadership by those who regard him as over-anxious to do a deal
with the Christian Democrats and Socialists.
</TEXT>
