<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / International Company News: Hollinger suffers loss of
CDollars 32m in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOLLINGER, the Canadian listed holding company controlled by Mr Conrad
Black, proprietor of the UK's Daily Telegraph newspaper, suffered a
first-quarter loss as a result of a write-down in the value of its
recently-sold investment in Britain's United Newspapers.
Hollinger sold its 9 per cent stake in United Newspapers in April for
substantially less than it paid when it started accumulating the shares in
early 1989.
The first-quarter loss was CDollars 31.7m (USDollars 26.4), or 63 cents a
share, against earnings of CDollars 17.4m, or 24 cents, a year earlier.
Operating earnings fell to CDollars 6.6m from CDollars 11.3m, due to an
CDollars 8.1m jump in tax provisions, while revenues rose 9 per cent to
CDollars 209m.
Hollinger said the higher tax provision was due to tax loss carry-forwards
at the Telegraph in the first half of 1991. Tax rates are likely to be more
similar in the second half.
Losses from the United sale are likely to be more than offset by gains from
the forthcoming public offering of 20m shares in the Telegraph group. The
Telegraph issue is expected to raise about Pounds 75m.
Hollinger has also recently raised CDollars 135m through the sale of four
series of preferred shares in Canada as part of its efforts to reduce debt.
Mr Christopher Ondaatje, the Canadian financier, is bidding to buy back full
control of the Toronto investment firm that bears his name, writes Robert
Gibbens in Montreal.
Mr Ondaatje was a co-founder of Loewen Ondaatje McCutcheon in 1970, and he
is offering CDollars 1.80 a share for all the firm's stock. He sold his
original stake late in 1987 at CDollars 9 a share. His bid competes with an
offer from two Vancouver businessmen who would buy 28 per cent of the LOM
shares from five management shareholders at Dollars 1.64 a share.
</TEXT>
