<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Diamond's hard-won reputation faces tough challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIAMOND may no longer be the hardest substance in the world now that US
researchers have made small quantities of carbon nitride, a synthetic
material which appears from preliminary tests to be as hard as or even
harder than diamond.
If the discovery at North-western University in Illinois is confirmed, it
will shatter diamond's romantic reputation for supreme hardness, which most
scientists had assumed would last for ever. But it could lead to many
industrial applications for carbon nitride (CN) as an ultrahard coating
which could resist wear better than any other material.
The Northwestern project started after physicists at the University of
California, Berkeley, published a computer prediction saying the hexagonal
crystal structure of CN - containing carbon and nitrogen atoms in a
three-to-four ratio - would be harder than the cubic crystals of diamond,
which is pure carbon.
The researchers have made a thin film of carbon nitride by a technique known
as reactive sputtering. This involves firing carbon atoms from a graphite
electrode at a smooth metal surface in a low-pressure atmosphere of
nitrogen.
Although there is not yet enough crystalline material to do a definitive
hardness test, preliminary results suggest that CN will live up to its
computer model. The coating has come through standard wear-resistance tests
without a scratch.
The university recently received a three-year grant from the US National
Science Foundation to make more carbon nitride and investigate its
applications. It could give a protective surface to a variety of materials
including cutting tools and bearings.
Mr Ming-Show Wong of North-western's industrial research laboratory sees a
large potential market in extending the life of computer disks with an
ultrahard coating.
But if carbon nitride is to become more than a scientific curiosity some
questions remain. For example, whether it can be manufactured at a
reasonable cost and how well it bonds to other materials.
A serious difficulty with diamond coatings is getting them to stick securely
to the substrate, says Mr Alan Collins, a physicist at King's College,
London. 'If carbon nitride sticks well to a large number of substrates, it
could be a winner.'
However, carbon nitride still exists only as a microscopic coating and as
yet there is no practical technique for making gem-sized crystals. So for
the foreseeable future diamonds remain a girl's best friend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
