<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / The Lex Column: Currencies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Denmark rejection of the Maastricht treaty will come as a shock to European
currency and bond markets which have been priming themselves for an opposite
result since the middle of last week. The immediate effect will not only be
an almost certain slide in the price of Danish bonds. The currency could
move closer to its floor within the ERM. But Denmark's problems will be as
nothing to the rethinking that must now begin on the prospects for European
currency union and convergence of interest rates.
The most likely response will be a flow of funds into the D-Mark which will
leave high-interest currencies exposed, especially the lira because of
Italy's political problems, the Ecu, and the Nordic currencies which are not
members of the system. It would be rash, however, for markets to expect an
early realignment. This is a taboo subject.
As for the UK it is left somewhere in the middle with a high budget deficit
and high core inflation rate offsetting the attraction of political
stability that followed the election. Doubtless sterling will continue to
enjoy the support of that stability to some degree. whether it will be
enough to secure inflows sufficient to fund the PSBR at current gilt yields
is another matter.
</TEXT>
