<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Patten orders urgent review of school technology
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, yesterday launched an urgent review
of the curriculum for technology at schools in England and Wales, following
a highly critical report by the schools inspectorate.
The report highlights the ill-effects of the devolution of most funding from
local education authorities to schools, one of the government's key
education policies.
'At a time when teachers need advice and support with the introduction of
technology,' said the inspectorate, 'many local authorities have reduced the
number of advisory teachers and closed technology in-service training
centres, often in order to reduce expenditure and to enable them to delegate
more money to schools'.
The inspectorate found that at primary level much technology teaching was
constrained 'by the teachers' limited technological capability,' while at
secondary level barely half of all lessons in design and technology observed
were satisfactory or better, with lesson planning in the subject
'piecemeal'.
At both levels, schools had difficulty in providing challenging work for
more advanced pupils.
In a Commons written answer, Mr Patten said the review, to be conducted by
the inspectorate, was intended 'to specify more clearly the skills and
knowledge which pupils should acquire at each stage' and 'to enhance the
practical element' in the curriculum.
'I am determined to increase teachers' expectations of childrens'
abilities,' said Mr Patten.
A new curriculum framework for school technology is expected to be
introduced in 1994 for pupils up to 14, and a year later for pupils over 14.
This will involve new syllabuses for GCSE.
Mr Patten's action was also promoted by advice from the National Curriculum
Council, an advisory body, which urged a review to relate conceptual work in
technology more closely with practical skills, and to reduce the complexity
of the curriculum.
The Engineering Council, which published a sharply critical report on the
issue last month, said: 'technology should be a subject in which students
design and make useful products or systems, developing their ability to
solve practical problems.'
Independent boarding schools should be eligible to opt for grant-maintained
status and become fully-fledged state schools, according to the director of
the Independent Schools Information Service.
Pupil numbers at independent boarding schools have fallen by more than 10
per cent in the last three years, and the call is seen as further evidence
of the plight of the sector.
</TEXT>
