<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Bank will not censure BCCI case
broker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England has shrugged off concern expressed by a Commons'
committee and decided it cannot discipline a firm of brokers who acted for
the Western Isles Islands Council which lost Pounds 24m in the Bank of
Credit and Commerce International collapse.
A letter sent to the clerk of the Treasury committee says the Bank judges
evidence on the role of R P Martin, 'still to be conflicting, and
insufficient to find the allegations against R P Martin proven'.
The Bank's comments follow a report by the committee last December, which
said there was prima facie evidence to invalidate the Bank of England's
initial conclusion - that there was no evidence of a breach by brokers of
the code of practice for the City's wholesale financial markets.
The Treasury select committee has not been set up since the general election
but the Bank's letter will be made available to MPs.
Some MPs may remain uneasy about the role of the brokers acting for local
authorities investing in BCCI, Mr Terence Higgins, former chairman of the
Treasury committee, yesterday welcomed revisions to the code that the Bank
announced last week.
The committee called in its report for the Bank to re-open investigations
into R P Martin. In response, the Bank held further discussions with
individuals at the broker's Edinburgh offices and with staff at the Western
Isles Council.
It found that the only area not disputed was the absence of taping of
conversations in R P Martin's Edinburgh offices - but that did not amount to
a breach, the Bank said.
However, the new code 'strongly recommends' taping of dealers' conversations
and the letter says Bank officials have discussed with R P Martin its policy
on taping 'and will be asking for a review of this policy in the light of
the revised code'.
The committee's concerns over R P Martin centred on a trip to the Western
Isles made by a BCCI representative with a representative of the brokers.
The MPs said that, 'joint visits, however arranged, may be taken as an
endorsement of the borrowing counterparty by the broker. While we completely
accept that it is for depositing counterparties to assess creditworthiness,
it is still important that brokers take no action which may be
misunderstood.'
In its letter to the committee, the Bank says such concerns have been
reflected in the revised code.
</TEXT>
