<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / DPP urges Lord Mackay to widen advocacy rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Barbara Mills QC, director of public prosecutions, and Sir James Nursaw
QC, head of the Government Legal Service, yesterday called on the Lord
Chancellor to give barristers in the employed sector the right to appear as
advocates in the higher courts.
In a joint submission to Lord Mackay, they argue that if he approves a Bar
Council rule that bans all employed barristers from appearing in the higher
courts he will shut the door on wider advocacy rights for Crown Prosecution
Service and government barristers forever.
This would be inconsistent with recent advice from his advisory committee
that CPS lawyers should be granted advocacy rights at some stage. Mrs Mills
and Sir James suggest Lord Mackay should ask the Bar to amend its rule to
reflect this.
Granting rights of audience to employed lawyers would both improve the
administration of justice and be in the public interest, they claim.
At the moment, more than 60 per cent of instructions to counsel are returned
just before the hearing so that a new and possibly unknown barrister is
brought in at the last minute. If rights of audience were available to
employed lawyers, in some cases it would be possible to use an experienced
GLS or CPS advocate with knowledge of the case.
The Bar is vehemently opposed to CPS lawyers having advocacy rights in the
Crown Court. It fears the CPS would take on the bulk of prosecution work
itself and deprive young barristers in private practice of much of their
bread and butter income, putting the future of an independent Bar at risk.
The CPS says it is the Bar's largest client and has a vested interest in
ensuring that it survives. Mrs Mills says it would undertake no more than
15-20 per cent of Crown Court prosecution work with all major trials
continuing to be handled by private practitioners.
Their joint submission follows a recommendation made to the Lord Chancellor
last month by Sir Gordon Borrie, the outgoing director general of fair
trading that the Bar's rule was anti-competitive and should be removed.
Although it is now more than four years since Lord Mackay first signalled
the end of the Bar's 200-year monopoly on advocacy in the higher courts his
office said yesterday that he was still several months away from a final
decision on the issue.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
