<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Investment sales methods under attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INVESTMENT ombudsman yesterday strongly criticised selling methods in
the industry, saying that most disputes arose out of misunderstandings of
what clients had requested.
The ombudsman, Mr Richard Youard, said cases referred to him had decreased
in the year to the end of March to 67, from 89 in the previous year. The
number of cases resolved rose from 98 to 100. But there had been a big
increase in the amount paid out in compensation, with a rise from Pounds
22,655 to Pounds 114,272. The largest amount paid in a settlement was Pounds
25,031, up from Pounds 8,715 last year. About half the cases were resolved
in favour of the complainant.
Mr Youard said the fall in complaints - which contrasts with a marked
increase in criticism of banks, building societies and insurance companies -
was probably caused by the recession, which discouraged stock market
investment while increasing reliance on banks and building societies.
In his criticism of selling methods he referred to the lack of notes taken
by salesmen at interviews. 'It's quite possible for a salesman to be a
salesman and an adviser at the same time but it's difficult, and because a
salesman instinctively sells, things can go wrong.'
Mr Youard also criticised the level of cost disclosure for unit-trust
products. These comments may have an impact on the Securities and
Investments Board's review of retail investment regulation, which has
settled on disclosure rules for life assurance but has yet to make firm
proposals on unit-trust disclosure.
The ombudsman said the 'health warning' on unit-trust marketing material,
which says that the price of units can go down as well as up, was
misunderstood. 'What in my view, is required as a matter of urgency is the
abandonment of the present warning and its substitution in a prominent form
by such words as 'you may get back less than you invested'.'
He also found that the 'bid/offer' price-spread for unit trusts was
misunderstood. He said he would be delighted if the expression were
abandoned for ever 'since I have seen far too many cases where it has been
wholly misunderstood by the investor'. It should be substituted, he said,
with a simple statement that the cost of the manager's services would be
deducted from the investment on the first day.
The investment ombudsman deals with disputes between customers and members
of Imro, the Investment Managers' Regulatory Office.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
