<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Labour council chief warms to contracting-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MARKED shift in Labour's attitude to the contracting-out of services to
the private sector was signalled yesterday by one of the party's senior
local government leaders.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, head of the Labour-dominated Association of Metropolitan
Authorities and leader of Newcastle upon Tyne council, said that quality of
service, not the identity of its provider, should be Labour's prime concern.
Mr Beecham told the the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and
Accountancy's annual conference that he conceded 'pressure on the
competitive tendering front will continue'. He added: 'Local government has
to recognise that the public is not intrinsically interested in who is
providing a service but in what kind of service they receive.'
Labour fought the election committed to ending compulsory competitive
tendering (CCT), a policy bitterly opposed by unions in local government.
Instead, on Mr Beecham's initiative, it proposed to establish a quality
commission charged with monitoring and spreading best practice. The
commission would have been empowered to enforce tendering only as a last
resort.
Mr Beecham's endorsement of CCT yesterday was far from grudging. Pointing to
the division it necessitated between a council's roles as purchaser and
provider of services, he claimed it had 'caused a re-examination of
performance, with generally beneficial results'.
The emphasis, he said, ought to be on quality. 'The promotion of quality
should assist local authorities in the competitive process, providing we
ensure that quality is written into contract specifications, (and) that we
are equipped to monitor performance whether of our own workforce or the
private sector.'
A report last week by the Institute of Public Finance revealed that a
majority of local authorities now contract out at least one of their main
services to the private sector. A fifth of them were found to contract out
three or more services. It also showed private-sector competition to be
intensifying.
Mr Beecham's remarks will have wide ramifications, both among Labour
councillors and the party's soon-to-be-elected leadership.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
