<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Mackay set to rule on rent arrears law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD MACKAY, the Lord Chancellor, is likely to decide by the end of the
month on reforms to the controversial law which allows landlords in England
and Wales to recover rent due from defaulting tenants from previous tenants
of the same property.
The pressure imposed by the existing system prompted an announcement
yesterday from Grand Metropolitan Estates, the property subsidiary of the UK
food and drinks group, that it intends to waive the liability for many of
its tenants of public houses.
Lord Mackay is likely to recommend that tenants should only guarantee the
rents of their immediate successor. The changes, proposed by the Law
Commission in 1988, are unlikely to become law before the end of next year.
Tenants have been lobbying for a change in the law for the past six months.
Some have received rent demands for premises they occupied up to 25 years
ago. Landlords have been equally outspoken about the need to preserve a law
underpinning the security of a property's rental income.
The Conservative party manifesto, which promised to consider putting the Law
Commission's proposals into effect, suggested that the changes would apply
to new commercial leases. Lord Mackay is likely to recommend that the
principles be applied to any assignment that takes place once the
legislation is implemented.
GrandMet Estates will offer many of its 8,000 tenants the right to waive
their liability for rent owed by successors, in return for the payment of 10
per cent of the premium received on assigning a lease. Corporate tenants and
those with more than one pub will not be offered the new terms.
Mr Bob Williams, chairman of GrandMet Estates, said he did not support a
general change in the the law, which he felt was important for long-term
property investors. He felt, however, that the existing law was
inappropriate for individuals.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
