<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Shake-up in business support: Enterprise agencies' umbrella
organisation to scale back direct involvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS IN the Community, the umbrella body for Britain's local enterprise
agencies, plans to reduce its direct involvement with the agencies.
BITC hopes to encourage the 300-plus agencies - which provide advice and
training to start-ups and small businesses, with backing from the private
sector - to create their own regional and national organisations.
If the body's board approves the proposal at a meeting next week, there are
plans for a conference of heads of enterprise agencies to launch an
agency-run organisation in October.
The ending of BITC's special relationship with the enterprise agency
movement marks a further significant shift in the business-support network.
The body plans to concentrate more of its resources on working with its
members - private-sector companies involved in community activities - and to
reflect the broader community concerns of these companies.
In a recent confidential draft of its proposals the body said: 'BITC has
widened its involvement to include such things as education, the environment
and general community affairs. It is therefore no longer automatic that BITC
and the enterprise agencies will always share the same priorities.'
It is also responding to the growing diversity of business-support
organisations. This means it is no longer appropriate for it to be linked
too closely with just one provider of business support. It will continue to
help the enterprise agencies while the national network is set up, but plans
to extend its support to chambers of commerce, training and enterprise
councils, and the Prince's Youth Business Trust.
It also plans to continue to provide help to the enterprise agencies during
the change-over period to their own national network.
Mr David Grayson, BITC managing director of operations, said: 'We are not
walking away from the enterprise agencies.' Preparations for an end to the
relationship and discussions with leaders of the enterprise agencies had
been under way since 1988.
However, reaction to the proposal from the enterprise agencies was mixed.
'We will lose out by not having someone to represent our views to
government,' commented one director.
Another said: 'Some agencies have wanted to get away from the BITC link but
others will be disappointed. I am worried that this will reduce the impact
of the work that has been done to encourage big companies to help small
businesses. The agencies will have to work out how to put over their
message.'
</TEXT>
