<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Radioactive waste repository delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK NIREX, the nuclear-waste consortium, yesterday an-nounced a one-year
delay in submitting its planning application for Britain's first underground
repository for radio-active waste.
Nirex said the delay was because it had insufficient information on the
hydro-geology of the Sellafield area of Cumbria, its preferred site.
The delay is not expected to increase the cost on the Pounds 2.5bn project
significantly.
Nirex had expected that its first four test boreholes would provide enough
information for it to submit a planning application late this year.
But water flows at deep levels seemed to be 'slow and sluggish', Mr Michael
Folger, Nirex managing director, said yesterday. This made it much more
important to obtain information from two proposed test boreholes on
fellsides in the Lake District National Park.
The Lake District Special Planning Board has refused permission for drilling
because of fears of harm to the landscape, noise and disturbance. Nirex is
lodging an appeal, which may trigger a public inquiry by the Department of
the Environment.
Nirex said it did not expect to drill the boreholes before the first half of
next year. It now aims to make a decision on a planning application for the
repository by autumn next year. The revised target date for the
800-metre-deep repository to begin operating is 2006.
Cumbria County Council, which is pressing for a more wide-ranging inquiry,
welcomed the delay. Friends of the Earth, the environmental group, said
Nirex must now realise it had the wrong design in the wrong place, and
should back down.
Britain is to approach the Commonwealth of Independent States for permission
to send a research vessel to the Kara Sea, south of the Arctic Ocean, where
radioactive waste was dumped by the former Soviet Union.
British officials want to study the movement of radioactivity from the dump
area. Radioactivity has been detected in the sea around Greenland, and
scientists believe contamination may be spreading.
</TEXT>
