<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / SFO has not pursued Vaduz connection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH investigators probing the collapse of companies controlled by Robert
Maxwell have yet to contact the Liechtenstein lawyers associated with many
of the secretive companies in the group.
Liechtenstein lawyers are normally reluctant to reveal information about
their clients, who tend to be wealthy people seeking to hide assets from tax
collectors. But the tiny alpine principality - wedged between Austria and
Switzerland - does not want to be a haven for serious crime, and Mr
Maxwell's Liechtenstein associates made clear as long ago as January that
they were eager to co-operate on the case with British investigators.
However, Mr Werner Keicher, a lawyer in the Vaduz-based trust advisory firm,
Allgemeines Treuunternehmen (General Trust), said this week that he had not
yet been approached by the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) or any other British
authorities.
Mr Keicher is a director of the Maxwell Foundation, which was the main
Liechtenstein vehicle used by Mr Maxwell to control many of his interests.
Mr Maxwell also set up through Allgemeines Treuunternehmen at least six
other Liechtenstein-based foundations, at least one of which was used to
conceal the source of funds for propping up the price of Maxwell
Communication Corporation shares.
Under Liechtenstein law, lawyers can co-operate with foreign investigations
only if the beneficiaries of the foundations waive their right to secrecy or
if the foreign government concerned requests co-operation in connection with
a criminal inquiry.
The formal procedure for making an official request for co-operation from a
foreign country is quite complicated, passing through various agencies of
the two countries concerned. Inquiries also have to be put in very precise
terms that comply with, in this case, Liechtenstein law.
Mr Keicher said he had the impression that the British authorities were
well-informed about the Liechtenstein side of the Maxwell story. 'There are
no assets here, no money. Perhaps they decided it was not worth it,' he
said.
The Serious Fraud Office yesterday refused to comment, saying the matter
concerned operational details of its investigation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
