<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Investigators probe network of 'war chests'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTS of Fivetell, one of the companies being examined by
investigators trying to find assets outside the control of the
administrators to the collapsed Maxwell empire, provide an insight into the
activities controlled by members of the family.
Fivetell was created by Robert Maxwell in 1984 to purchase a substantial
stake in Derby County Football Club, which he bought after a winding-up
petition earlier that year was withdrawn. Headington Investments, one of the
main Maxwell holding companies, had a substantial shareholding in Fivetell.
Mr Kevin Maxwell and Mr Ian Maxwell are listed as the two directors of the
company in the latest documents filed with Companies House on February 25
this year. Both are also shown as directors of another company called
Panlor, and Mr Kevin Maxwell is also a director of Oxford United Football
Club.
The majority stakes in Panlor are owned by Pandora, the wife of Mr Kevin
Maxwell, and Laura, the wife of Mr Ian Maxwell.
Mr Kevin Maxwell is shown as having held more than 270 other company
directorships, and Mr Ian Maxwell is shown as holding 170.
Mr Ian Maxwell is also listed as a shareholder in Fivetell, while Mr Kevin
Maxwell is shown to have shareholdings in London &amp; Bishopsgate Holdings,
Marblue, Newton, Chambers &amp; Co, Oxford United Football Club and Sheenwood
First Nominees.
The accounts of Fivetell for the year to May 31 1991 show that a loan of
Pounds 3m - believed to be unsecured - was made after the accounts were
approved.
Fivetell also had an outstanding loan of Pounds 622,000 last year to
Publishing and Databank Consultants, controlled by the Maxwell estate. The
loan has since been repaid.
There may also have been a loan - the status of which is disputed - for
about Pounds 2m from Fivetell to Oxford United Football Club.
The Fivetell accounts show a pre-tax profit of Pounds 726,000 for the year,
and a deficiency of assets of Pounds 1.4m.
Fivetell appears to have been used to hold the family stakes in Oxford
United as well as Derby County. Both stakes were sold through Robert
Maxwell's estate, which is in receivership.
Documents for Panlor - which Mr Kevin Maxwell and Mr Ian Maxwell are shown
to be directors of - show that the company was created on December 20 last
year. No accounts have yet been filed, but the documents show the two
'allottees', holding 49 shares each, are Mrs Pandora Maxwell and Mrs Laura
Maxwell.
Mr Neil Cooper of Robson Rhodes, the accountancy firm, who is liquidator to
Bishopsgate Investment Management, manager and trustee of the Maxwell
pension funds, said he was aware of a number of 'little puddles of money
left around' in different companies and trusts which may have been 'war
chests'.
'We still don't know the full ramifications of any of these strange
companies,' he said. 'But there is still a great deal of energy being spent
investigating and tracking them down.'
</TEXT>
