<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / World Trade News: Bush seeks extension of MFN status for
China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush announced last night he would seek extension of Most
Favoured Nation (MFN) trading status for China in spite of mounting
criticism in the US of Beijing's human rights record.
The president was obliged by law to act no later than today. Congress now
has 90 days in which to block implementation of MFN status, which allows a
wide range of Chinese goods to be imported under special preferences.
A White House statement issued yesterday evening acknowledged that the
decision would be controversial, as it was with the last extension a year
ago.
The US, the statement said, wanted to elicit a faster pace and a broader
scope for human rights improvements in China. Withdrawal of MFN would
achieve neither of these objectives.
Mr Bush has frequently been criticised for his staunch support of the
Chinese regime, especially after the Tiananmen Square massacres three years
ago. Further aggravations to bilateral relations have stemmed from Chinese
missile sales and nuclear testing, the most recent only last month.
</TEXT>
