<PROFILE>_AN-CFCAXADPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920603
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Danes say No to Maastricht: Narrow vote against treaty
blocks pact on European political and monetary union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DANISH VOTERS last night threw into confusion the future plans of the
European Community by rejecting the Maastricht Treaty and thereby blocking
the current EC accord on European political and monetary union.
The surprise result - by the narrowest of margins in a referendum - will
force the other 11 EC states to renegotiate the accord if, as seems likely,
a modified form of the treaty is to go ahead.
The painstakingly-negotiated treaty, requiring unanimous agreement, was
intended to become the EC's new constitution, replacing the 34-year-old
founding Treaty of Rome. It was to have led to a single currency by 1999,
the gradual building of a common foreign and security policy, and eventually
to a common defence policy.
Mr Joao de Deus Pinheiro, foreign minister of Portugal, current holder of
the EC presidency, expressed deep disappointment at the Danish vote, which
is binding on the Copenhagen government. EC foreign ministers will hold an
emergency meeting in Oslo tomorrow, on the sidelines of scheduled Nato
talks, to discuss the implications.
Mr Poul Schluter, Danish prime minister, said: 'I am convinced that the
other 11 members will carry out the Maastricht treaty, so it is up to us to
get as much out of the situation as possible.'
In London, the vote was being assessed by Mr John Major, the prime minister.
Downing Street pointed out that the UK government had yet to hear officially
what the Danish administration planned to do. The outcome of the referendum
was welcomed by vocal critics at Westminster of the Maastricht accord.
Mr Major and Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, will today discuss the
matter, which could have a significant impact on the UK presidency of the
Community, which starts at the beginning of next month.
The Danish vote also throws into doubt the aim of Irish prime minister
Albert Reynolds for a strong Yes vote in his country's referendum in two
weeks' time. Mr Dick Spring, Irish opposition Labour party leader, said last
night that Ireland should consider postponing its vote.
In yesterday's referendum, 50.7 per cent voted against the treaty, with 49.3
per cent voting in favour. Turnout was 82.9 per cent.
In rejecting the Maastricht treaty, the voters ignored the advice of the
political establishment, both sides of industry and an almost unanimous
press. The referendum cannot be overturned by the Folketing (parliament).
Financial markets, which had counted on a Yes vote, were also surprised by
the outcome, which confounded the opinion pollsters, whose surveys in the
past few days had pointed to a narrow victory for Maastricht.
Other EC governments including the UK, Germany and France, have said in
recent weeks that a Danish No vote would not stop them from implementing
European political union. But a senior EC official said last night: 'There
is an insurmountable requirement that if any of the 12 member states does
not ratify it, Maastricht goes down the drain. We have made no contingency
planning for a rejection.'
Currency and bond markets reacted cautiously to early indications of the
Danish vote. Dealers reported buying interest in other member currencies of
the European Monetary System, pushing the Danish krone down a little. The
Danish government benchmark 10-year bond fell two points to 99.80 in
inter-bank trading in Copenhagen.
Mr Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, foreign minister, who fought hard to persuade
voters to accept the treaty, said: 'We face a very difficult time. We must
now think things through very carefully.'
He said it was too early to say whether the government might consider trying
to reverse last night's vote in a new referendum.
The Danish vote may have a significant effect on opinion in the other Nordic
countries, such as Sweden and Finland, which have already applied for EC
membership.
Danes say No, Page 3
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
