<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Hongkong Bank increases bid for Midland to Pounds 3.9bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONGKONG and Shanghai Banking Corporation increased its bid for Midland Bank
to Pounds 3.9bn yesterday, offering for the first time to pay shareholders
partly in cash.
Midland's rival suitor, Lloyds Bank, responded by hinting that it may
improve its proposed terms, if it is cleared to bid by the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission. Mr William Purves, HSBC chairman, said in Toronto his
bank's new bid terms were 'definitely the final offer'.
Although Hongkong Bank is free, under UK Takeover Panel rules, to renew its
bid in the autumn if it does not succeed now, Mr Purves added: 'If Midland
shareholders turn us down and choose to wait for the outcome of the
Monopolies inquiry to see if Lloyds is allowed to bid, those shareholders
should not assume that we will make another bid then.'
For each 100 shares in Midland, shareholders are being offered 120 shares in
the new Hongkong Bank Holding Company after the merger and either Pounds 65
of bonds or Pounds 65 in cash. The offer values each Midland share at 480p.
Last night Midland closed at 452p, up 31p.
The terms were welcomed by Midland and Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive, who
said the bank would recommend shareholders accept the offer. Midland says it
is increasingly worried about the effect on its business of a prolonged
takeover battle.
Mr Brian Pitman, Lloyds chief executive, who was also in Toronto, at a
meeting of the International Monetary Conference, said his board would be
meeting on Friday.
He hinted Lloyds was likely to offer. 'We will have to tell Midland's
shareholders what our offer is worth now and what it could be worth later,'
he said.
However, last night Mr Pearse called on Lloyds to withdraw its proposed bid.
Speaking on BBC Radio's Financial World Tonight, he said: 'Lloyds is now an
irrelevancy. There is now no doubt in my mind that the chances of its
succeeding on competition grounds in its bid for Midland are virtually nil.
It would save us all a lot of irrelevant work if it withdraw.'
In the City, some analysts said the new offer tipped the odds in favour of
the Hongkong Bank bid succeeding. Shareholders remained undecided. One large
institution said: 'Frankly we would much rather be shareholders in Lloyds
Bank. The new Hongkong offer is quite rich and quite tempting but Lloyds is
a natural holding for us and a more logical fit for us than a vague global
bank.'
Hongkong Bank has brought forward the acceptance date on its offer by nearly
two weeks to June 25, giving shareholders little more than three weeks to
decide whether to accept the offer or wait until the autumn in the hope that
Lloyds will be cleared to launch its own bid.
Hongkong Bank is now offering slightly more than Lloyds' proposed terms for
each Midland share, but Lloyds is widely expected to raise its offer above
500p if it gets clearance.
Hongkong Bank's original offer to Midland shareholders gave them 118 shares
in the combined bank and Pounds 50 worth of bonds. valued each Midland share
at 401p.
One important feature of the new offer is that it makes Hongkong Bank bonds
much more attractive to institutions by improving their yield from 1.6 per
cent to 2.4 per cent above gilts and arranging for them to be underwritten
by Credit Suisse First Boston, Schroders, Cazenove, and SG Warburg.
Campaigns will be pressed to a conclusion, Page 24
Bonds that carry more generous terms, Page 24
Offer seen as an astute move in colony, Page 24
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
