<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Howard says at least 2,000 DoE staff will relocate to
Docklands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday hardened its commitment to relocate at least 2,000
civil servants in Docklands as ministers sought to give a breathing space
for the administrators of the failed Canary Wharf development.
Separately, Ernst &amp; Young, the administrators, made 44 of Canary Wharf's 198
office staff redundant. They said further redundancies among office staff
would follow 'as certain of the group's activities are completed'. Most of
the 218 estate management staff at Canary Wharf will keep their jobs, they
said. 'The joint administrators do not envisage any material reductions to
these employees as they wish to maintain the full services to existing
tenants.'
In the House of Commons, Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, said
Canary Wharf was among three sites under study for the move by civil
servants from the Department of the Environment. The others were Harbour
Exchange and East India Dock, both on the Isle of Dogs.
Mr Howard said he expected to conclude soon an outline deal to lease space
at one of the sites. Officials said a decision was likely before the end of
this month. He repeated that there could be no subsidy, 'hidden or
otherwise', in the deal. He also said the government would go ahead with the
extension of the Jubilee line only if the owners of Canary Wharf contributed
the Pounds 400m agreed previously by Olympia &amp; York.
Ministerial colleagues said Mr Howard's announcement - which included
details of a prospective move of another few hundred civil servants from the
Department of Trade and Industry - was designed to emphasise the
government's confidence in Docklands. That in turn should help give the
administrators of Canary Wharf a breathing space in their efforts to salvage
the project.
The environment secretary repeated that the government would not intervene
directly in any rescue operation. But Lord Wakeham, the Lord Privy Seal, is
understood to be in active contact with potential purchasers of Canary
Wharf.
Mr Howard said the move by his staff and the DTI's Radio Communications
Agency could be followed in the longer term by the relocation of civil
servants from other departments.
He also signalled he was in discussions with the Treasury on possible
compensation - perhaps travel allowances or relocation expenses - for civil
servants affected by the move.
One minister involved in the negotiations said the high quality of
accommodation available at Canary Wharf made it a frontrunner. The
government would have to satisfy the National Audit Office that it was the
best value for money.
Mr Howard, who faced pressure from some Conservative MPs to confirm that the
government would go ahead with the Jubilee line extension, said he was
confident that the owners of Canary Wharf would come up with the agreed
contribution.
The maintenance of Canary Wharf will be discussed this week at meetings
between individual tenants and the administrators. The tenants will also
seek assurances about the security of the project and the payment of rent on
former properties, one of O&amp;Y's inducements for them to move to Canary
Wharf.
</TEXT>
